Under the Sindh Payment of Wages Act 2015, an employer may make deductions from wages only if the deduction is authorized by the Act.  Section 7(2) specifies the permissible kinds of deductions as follows:

* (a) Fines;  
* (b) Deductions for absence from duty;  
* (c) Deductions for damage to or loss of goods (or money) expressly entrusted to the employee and directly attributable to his neglect or default;  
* (d) Deductions for amenities and services supplied by the employer as authorized by the Government (excluding tools and raw materials);  
* (e) Deductions for recovery of advances or adjustment of over‑payments of wages;  
* (f) Deductions of income‑tax payable by the employee;  
* (g) Deductions required by order of a court or other competent authority;  
* (h) Deductions for subscriptions to, and repayment of advances from, any recognised provident fund;  
* (i) Deductions for payments to co‑operative societies approved by the Government or to a scheme of insurance maintained by the Pakistan Post Office; and  
* (j) Deductions, with the employee’s written authorisation, for any war‑savings scheme approved by the Government.  

These are the only categories of deductions that may legally be made from an employee’s wages.  (Sindh Payment of Wages Act 2015, s. 7, p. 6)
